I want a web app for goldfishing a Magic: The Gathering Commander
deck — I want to test how consistently my deck delivers a good
opening hand.

Core behavior:
- Let me paste a Commander decklist in standard MTG text format
  (lines like "1 Sol Ring", "1 Command Tower", with a commander
  possibly marked separately). Parse it reliably and ignore any
  set codes or collector numbers.
- Draw a random 7-card opening hand. The commander starts in the
  command zone, so hands are drawn from the 99, not the full 100.
- Let me draw hands one at a time, redrawing as many times as I
  want, OR give a number N and have it draw that many hands at once
  so I can test a batch.
- London mulligan support so I can test mulligan decisions.
- Show each hand clearly and let me reshuffle/reset easily.

Analysis:
- For each hand, break down the cards by type — lands, creatures,
  instants, sorceries, artifacts, enchantments, planeswalkers — so
  I can see the composition at a glance.
- Across a batch of N hands, give me summary stats: average lands
  per hand, how often I hit a keepable land count, and the average
  type breakdown, so I can judge the deck's consistency.

Export:
- Let me export the drawn hands as CSV so I can save and analyze
  them in a spreadsheet — include the card lists per hand plus the
  per-hand and summary stats.

Make it clean and immediately usable, and handle a messy paste
(extra whitespace, blank lines, section headers) gracefully.